rrorists unfortunately this incomplete response has motivated a detrimental increase in the amount of information government keeps private or labels sensitive but unclassified we identify two distinct types of private information that are potentially useful to terrorists and identify the range of conditions under which sharing each can enhance counterterrorism efforts our results highlight the complex trade offs policy makers face in deciding how much openness is right in a world where protecting the people from terrorists has become a central duty of government download html+ go to site external http www informaworld com smpp se parent research terrorism insurgency and homeland security topics terrorism and counterterrorism search fsi search within everything courses events fellowships news op eds people publications research other pages publications of interest what should this fight be called metaphors of counterterrorism and their implications arie w kruglanski martha crenshaw jerrold m post jeff victoroff psychological science in the public interest vol 8 3 2007 pdf+ cover terror and beauty the european institute for mathematical methods in counterterrorism jonathan farley bridges vol 7 2005 html+ cover east asian regionalism in a new global context balancing representation and effectiveness donald k emmerson 2009 pdf+ madman nuclear alert secrecy signaling and safety in the october 1969 crisis the scott d sagan jeremi suri international security vol 27 4 2003 pdf+ cover support map & directions contact rss+ rss xml feeds freeman spogli institute for international studies encina hall 616 serra st stanford ca 94305 6055 tel 650 723 4581 fax 650 725 2592 mail code 6055
